i# CBRS Band: Unlicensed LTE/5G Band in the US		{{server_addr}}	{{server_port}}
i		{{server_addr}}	{{server_port}}
iThe challenge in building your own LTE network lies not in the		{{server_addr}}	{{server_port}}
itechnology but in legally acquiring radio spectrum resources. On the		{{server_addr}}	{{server_port}}
isoftware side, as early as 2014, solutions like		{{server_addr}}	{{server_port}}
hsrsRAN	URL:https://www.srslte.com/	{{server_addr}}	{{server_port}}
ibased on SDR (Software Defined Radio) for LTE transmission were		{{server_addr}}	{{server_port}}
iavailable, along with open-source core network software like		{{server_addr}}	{{server_port}}
hMagma	URL:https://magmacore.org/	{{server_addr}}	{{server_port}}
iand		{{server_addr}}	{{server_port}}
hOpen5GS	URL:https://open5gs.org/	{{server_addr}}	{{server_port}}
i.		{{server_addr}}	{{server_port}}
i		{{server_addr}}	{{server_port}}
iHowever, when it comes to radio spectrum, the frequencies used by LTE		{{server_addr}}	{{server_port}}
iand 5G mobile networks fall within licensed bands. To use them		{{server_addr}}	{{server_port}}
ilegally, you must apply to the local radio regulatory authority and		{{server_addr}}	{{server_port}}
ipay expensive spectrum usage fees (usually based on coverage area and		{{server_addr}}	{{server_port}}
ilocal population). Unless you live in a sparsely populated area, most		{{server_addr}}	{{server_port}}
ienthusiasts will be stopped at this step. If you transmit without		{{server_addr}}	{{server_port}}
iauthorization, you will interfere with operators using the same		{{server_addr}}	{{server_port}}
ifrequency, and the affected operators have a strong incentive to		{{server_addr}}	{{server_port}}
icollaborate with enforcement agencies to locate the source of		{{server_addr}}	{{server_port}}
iinterference and heavily fine you.		{{server_addr}}	{{server_port}}
i		{{server_addr}}	{{server_port}}
iIn 2017, however, the Federal Communications Commission (FCC) opened		{{server_addr}}	{{server_port}}
ithe 3550-3700 MHz band to the public, known as the CBRS (Citizens		{{server_addr}}	{{server_port}}
iBroadband Radio Service) band. Anyone who meets simple restrictions		{{server_addr}}	{{server_port}}
ican transmit on this band without prior authorization. Since this band		{{server_addr}}	{{server_port}}
icorresponds to LTE band 48 and 5G band n48, you can transmit LTE or 5G		{{server_addr}}	{{server_port}}
isignals on this band, allowing phones that support band 48 to connect,		{{server_addr}}	{{server_port}}
ithereby legally establishing your own LTE/5G network.		{{server_addr}}	{{server_port}}
i		{{server_addr}}	{{server_port}}
iIf many devices transmit on the same band without coordination, severe		{{server_addr}}	{{server_port}}
isignal interference will occur, rendering the band unusable for		{{server_addr}}	{{server_port}}
ieveryone. To address this, CBRS introduced the SAS system (Spectrum		{{server_addr}}	{{server_port}}
iAccess System) to manage all radio devices transmitting on the CBRS		{{server_addr}}	{{server_port}}
iband. SAS categorizes CBRS users into three levels:		{{server_addr}}	{{server_port}}
i		{{server_addr}}	{{server_port}}
i- Incumbent Access: Users who were authorized to use this band before		{{server_addr}}	{{server_port}}
i  2017 have the highest priority. These are typically satellite		{{server_addr}}	{{server_port}}
i  control stations and US Navy radars. If these users transmit on the		{{server_addr}}	{{server_port}}
i  CBRS band, all other users must yield.		{{server_addr}}	{{server_port}}
i- Priority Access: Users who have obtained priority usage rights for		{{server_addr}}	{{server_port}}
i  portions of the CBRS band through auctions have a lower priority		{{server_addr}}	{{server_port}}
i  than incumbent users but higher than all other users.		{{server_addr}}	{{server_port}}
i- General Authorized Access: All other users without prior		{{server_addr}}	{{server_port}}
i  authorization have the lowest priority and must yield to all other		{{server_addr}}	{{server_port}}
i  users.		{{server_addr}}	{{server_port}}
iAll CBRS band users, except the US Navy, must obtain authorization		{{server_addr}}	{{server_port}}
ifrom SAS before starting transmission, allowing SAS to dynamically		{{server_addr}}	{{server_port}}
iadjust frequency allocations in different areas to prevent mutual		{{server_addr}}	{{server_port}}
iinterference. For interference from US Navy radars, SAS uses signal		{{server_addr}}	{{server_port}}
ireceivers installed along the US coast to determine if the US Navy is		{{server_addr}}	{{server_port}}
iusing the band.		{{server_addr}}	{{server_port}}
i		{{server_addr}}	{{server_port}}
iTherefore, with a LTE/5G base station that supports the CBRS band and		{{server_addr}}	{{server_port}}
ican connect to SAS to obtain frequency allocations, you can legally		{{server_addr}}	{{server_port}}
itransmit signals and build your own mobile network.		{{server_addr}}	{{server_port}}
i		{{server_addr}}	{{server_port}}
iBut where can you buy such a device?		{{server_addr}}	{{server_port}}
i		{{server_addr}}	{{server_port}}
