i## Building the Magma Access Gateway (AGW)		{{server_addr}}	{{server_port}}
iMagma's Access Gateway manages the base station and forwards the base		{{server_addr}}	{{server_port}}
istation's data traffic to the internet. Note that Magma's core network		{{server_addr}}	{{server_port}}
ionly manages user information and does not handle data traffic, and		{{server_addr}}	{{server_port}}
ithe traffic from the Access Gateway does not pass through the core		{{server_addr}}	{{server_port}}
inetwork.		{{server_addr}}	{{server_port}}
i		{{server_addr}}	{{server_port}}
iFirst, prepare a system to run the Access Gateway. This system needs		{{server_addr}}	{{server_port}}
ito be configured with two network interfaces, where `eth0` is used for		{{server_addr}}	{{server_port}}
iremote management and connecting to the core network, and `eth1` is		{{server_addr}}	{{server_port}}
iused for connecting to the base station. If you're using a separate		{{server_addr}}	{{server_port}}
icomputer, you'll need to plug the base station's Ethernet cable into		{{server_addr}}	{{server_port}}
ithe `eth1` interface later, and Magma will automatically configure		{{server_addr}}	{{server_port}}
iDHCP to allow the base station to connect to the Access Gateway.		{{server_addr}}	{{server_port}}
iHowever, since I'm using a virtual machine on Proxmox VE, I chose to		{{server_addr}}	{{server_port}}
iplace the additional `eth1` interface in a VLAN and set up the		{{server_addr}}	{{server_port}}
icorresponding VLAN and IP on the main router. This way, I can ping the `eth1`		{{server_addr}}	{{server_port}}
iIP from any machine on my local network, meaning the base station can		{{server_addr}}	{{server_port}}
ibe plugged into any port on my main switch.		{{server_addr}}	{{server_port}}
i		{{server_addr}}	{{server_port}}
iThis system must be installed with Ubuntu 20.04 because the Magma		{{server_addr}}	{{server_port}}
iAccess Gateway installation modifies many system configurations, and		{{server_addr}}	{{server_port}}
ithese modifications are only supported on Ubuntu 20.04.		{{server_addr}}	{{server_port}}
i		{{server_addr}}	{{server_port}}
iAfter installation, the system services and Magma together use about		{{server_addr}}	{{server_port}}
i1GB of memory, so a virtual machine with about 2-4GB of memory should		{{server_addr}}	{{server_port}}
ibe sufficient.		{{server_addr}}	{{server_port}}
i		{{server_addr}}	{{server_port}}
